      <h2>New Texas PHIN Portal Debuts - www.txphin.org</h2>
      <p class="date">Oct 05, 2009</p>
      <img src="images/birthday.gif" style='float: left; margin-right: 10px; '/>
      <div class='lede'>
        <p>On Monday, the 5th of October, the newest version of Texas' Public Health Information Network (PHIN) portal became available online.  This new website, located at www.txphin.org, will begin replacing older versions of public health applications that currently reside at other websites.  Two of the websites to be replaced are the old version of the PHIN Portal at texphin.dshs.state.tx.us and the even older HAN application at txhan.tdh.state.tx.us.  This new portal is being developed by the Texas Association of Local Health Officials (TALHO) and the Department of State Health Services (DSHS) as a collaborative project.  Work began in July of '09 and will continue indefinitely as more and more resources and applications are brought into the portal.</p>
        <p class='more'><a href=''>Read more about this article</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class='body'>
        <p>The PHIN concept was created by the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) and grew out of earlier work by the CDC on the Health Alert Network guidelines and various other public health technology initiatives.  The PHIN concept is now a collection of technological functionalities and resources useful to all areas of public health.  The new portal is a web-based implementation of the PHIN concept.  HAN is now simply a subcomponent of the PHIN Portal, www.txphin.org.  In time, more and more subcomponents will be added to the portal.</p>
        <p>The first subcomponent to be brought online within the PHIN Portal is the HAN application.  This section of the PHIN provides for the important alerting capabilities every public health department needs.  Online, on-demand training for this application will be available sometime during the week of Oct. 5th and will be accessible from within the PHIN Portal.</p>
        <p>More portal apps are soon to come.  A school surveillance application, RollCall, will be released soon.  This component contains epi tools for the analysis of school absentee data and school clinic ILI reports.  TALHO will be providing integration services to help school districts get their data into the PHIN on a daily basis.  Other portal apps coming soon include a calendar tool, FAQs, chat, and document sharing/storage.  Further in the future, such apps as RODS and ESSENCE will be made available through the portal. "Eventually, we would like this portal to become an invaluable tool for public health in Texas.  Our goal is to provide a type of web desktop that has all the applications and tools we and our partners need."</p>
        <p>In addition to new applications, the new PHIN Portal makes many big improvements in usability and functionality.  "Passwords won't expire every ninety days.  And getting a password reset no longer involves staff action.  There's a password reset link on the authentication page." says portal designer Jason Phipps.  He went on to highlight a few more improvements like better uptime and a simpler user interface.</p>
        <p>Much of the functionality won't be available on opening day, but DSHS and TALHO staff report that the HAN alerting portion of the portal is ready.  Each alerting entity will be contacted during the month of October and encouraged to view the available training and try out a test of the alerting functionality.  Developers also revealed that an export of the registered users of the old PHIN portal has been accomplished, though only names and email addresses were able to be transferred into the new system.  Email notices will be sent to each user asking them to visit the new portal to request a password reset, allowing them to establish a password on the new portal.  Those users' passwords on the old portal will remain the same.</p>
