      <h2>Latest Seasonal and H1N1 Flu Vaccine Info</h2>
      <h3>By Claire Ashton, Texas Assocation of Local Health Officials</h3>
      <p class="date">Oct 02, 2009</p>
      <div class='lede'>
        <p>As of October 2, 2009, the Texas Department of State Health Services (DSHS) classification for general flu activity in Texas – an aggregate count of both seasonal flu and H1N1,  is “widespread”.  The “widespread” classification is used when there are increases in flu-like illnesses and recent lab-confirmed flu cases in at least half of the state’s regions.  Based on the “2008-2009 Influenza Season Week 37 (September 13-19, 2009) Report” from The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), 99% of all subtyped influenza A viruses being reported to the organization were 2009 influenza A (H1N1) viruses.</p>
        <p class='more'><a href=''>Read more about this article</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class='body'>
        <p>Dr. David Lakey, DSHS Commissioner, recommends that people get seasonal flu vaccinations now and H1N1 vaccinations as they become available. The H1N1 vaccine is not intended to replace the seasonal flu vaccine – it is intended to be used alongside the seasonal flu vaccine.  While the seasonal flu vaccine is currently available throughout Texas, the H1N1 vaccine is not anticipated to be available to the public until the second week of October.  Limited quantities will be available, with availability increasing through November and December.  Seasonal flu vaccine production began before production of the new H1N1 vaccine variety.  This unusual situation of having two, separate flu vaccines for the 2009 season is unique.  Next year, the H1N1 flu strain will be included in the normal seasonal flu vaccine.</p>
        <p>According to the CDC, anyone who wants to reduce their chances of getting seasonal flu can get vaccinated.  It is strongly recommended that those people who are at high-risk for having serious seasonal flu-related complications and people who live with or care for those at high risk for serious complications get vaccinated each year.</p>
        <p>Those at high risk for seasonal flu include children ages 6 months through 18 years, those 50 and older, people with chronic medical conditions, residents of long-term care facilities and pregnant women.</p>
        <p>Seasonal flu vaccine is available in shot and nasal spray forms.  The nasal spray is a vaccine made with live, weakened flu viruses that do not cause the flu (sometimes called LAIV for "live attenuated influenza vaccine" or FluMist®). LAIV (FluMist®) is approved for use in healthy people 2-49 years of age who are not pregnant.  The shot is an inactivated vaccine (containing killed virus) that is given with a needle, usually in the arm. The flu shot is approved for use in people older than 6 months, including healthy people and people with chronic medical conditions.  Vaccination by either method takes about two weeks to become effective.</p>
        <p>Adverse reactions to the seasonal flu vaccine may include soreness, redness, and swelling where the shot was given, low grade fever, and aches, although if these problems occur they begin soon after the shot and only last one to two days.  These symptoms are reported to be rare.  CDC and several universities will be tracking incidence of adverse reactions through various means, including a follow-up study of 100,000 vaccine recipients and an automated health insurance claims data analysis system.</p>
        <p>When the CDC’s Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP) met in July 2009, they prioritized 5 key populations on which to focus vaccination efforts this fall in order to reduce the impact and spread of H1N1 including:</p>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>Pregnant women</li>
            <li>People who live with or care for children younger than 6 months of age</li>
            <li>Health care and emergency medical services personnel</li>
            <li>Persons between the ages of 6 months through 24 years of age</li>
            <li>People from ages 25 through 64 years who are at higher risk for novel H1N1 because of chronic health disorders or compromised immune systems</li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>According to the state’s health information helpline – Texans can now dial 2-1-1 to receive over the phone medical guidance – the H1N1 vaccine will be administered in one shot for those over the age of 10 and in two shots, given 30 days apart, for those under the age of 10.</p>
        <p>“We’ve been told that we’ll have about 15 million doses for Texas after all is said and done, but it won’t be available all at once,” said Commissioner Lakey.  The initial 3.4 million doses of H1N1 vaccine that were projected for the state of Texas by mid-October have been reduced to 1.7 million doses.  DSHS is partnering with 8 chain pharmacies; a strategic decision by the State in order to reach the most people.  The first doses of H1N1 vaccine will be allotted to providers who primarily treat 2-3 year-olds.  In the first H1N1 vaccine shipment, local health departments and districts can expect to share a divided 10,000 doses, with each agency receiving no less than 100 doses and no more than 700 doses.</p>
        <p>According to DSHS, the CDC is revising, on a daily basis, estimates on the amount of H1N1 vaccine to ship.</p>
