      <h2>TALHO INTRODUCES ALL-TERRAIN COMMUNICATIONS VEHICLE</h2>
      <h3>By Mandy Dunn, TALHO</h3>
      <p class="date">Oct 05, 2009</p>
      <img src="images/truck.png" style='float: left; margin: 10px; '/>
      <div class='lede'>
        <p>TALHO, the Texas Association of Local Health Officials, has released its All-Terrain Communications Vehicle – one of several Mobile Tactical Units (MTU) engineered by the organization’s Technology Department. This mobile platform houses communication and power equipment to assist during emergency response deployments.</p>
        <p>"While our power system looks like any other renewable energy system, on the inside it uses Lithium Iron Phosphate batteries that represent the latest and most reliable Lithium Ion technology," explains Scott Gostisha, Director of Network Operations at TALHO. "These batteries have a life-cycle that is six times more substantial than standard lithium batteries." </p>
        <p>The All-Terrain Communication Vehicle also utilizes a clean-burning propane generator and renewable energy resources in the form of both wind and solar power to recharge the battery bank.</p>
        <p class='more'><a href=''>Read more about this article</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class='body'>
        <p>In the event of a disaster, this MTU can reach hard-to-access locations to provide much-needed voice, video and data communication capabilities for surrounding areas through a wireless hot-spot.  Also, the communications vehicle can tie into both data centers and Emergency Operations Centers via hardline if necessary, explains Gostisha, who assisted in engineering the vehicle’s communications infrastructure.</p>
        <p>TALHO’s All-Terrain Communications Vehicle may be requested in preparation for a pending emergency situation, like a hurricane, or after disaster impact, depending on its availability.</p>
